PARAGRAPH.#text: CIT Group Inc. CIT has proven there is life after bankruptcy. Three years after emerging from Chapter 11 proceedings, the specialty business lender has wiped out more than $31 billion in high-cost debt, purged troubled assets and made headway on its quest to cut funding costs by raising more consumer deposits to finance its customers' loans. But CIT's work isn't finished. It continues to operate under restrictions from the Federal Reserve and faces increasing competition from larger regional lenders that are aggressively courting commercial borrowers with low-rate loans, a concern for investors worried about profit-margin pressure.

Headlines.Headline: BofA's Governance Change Promises in Settlement Raise Eyebrows

PARAGRAPH.#text: It could be Bank of America's BAC Golden Age of corporate governance, and investors will have all of 27 months to enjoy it. As part of the bank's proposed $2.43 billion settlement with investors over the vexed merger with Merrill Lynch, BofA agreed to temporary corporate governance reform, the fleeting nature of which drew criticism from governance experts. Bank of America said it will reform certain practices, including majority voting in director elections, annual "say on pay" voting by shareholders, annual disclosure of noncompliance with stock ownership guidelines, and policies for a board committee regarding future acquisitions, and the independence of the board's compensation committee and its compensation consultants.

Carl Icahn's failure to block Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer's tie-up with Spyglass Entertainment is the second time in a year he has struck out trying to stop a prepackaged bankruptcy reorganization. Headlines.Author: Aparajita Saha-Bubna
Headlines.Headline: CIT Closes In On Cheaper Loan But Funding Challenges Remain

#text: CIT Group Inc.

is closing in on a $3 billion loan that will replace its prohibitively costly credit facility, a legacy of its trip to bankruptcy court. While this cheaper debt will improve CIT's loan margins, the lender to small and midsize businesses continues to be hamstrung by a lack of cheap funding after emerging from bankruptcy protection in December. The longer it takes for CIT to right its funding model, the lower its chances of making it as a stand-alone company and the more likely it is that it will be bought by a bank looking to expand its lending business to midsize firms.

#text: NEW YORK (Dow Jones)--The softening market for bank stocks threatens to cool the TARP program's hot returns. Banks that have exited the government's Troubled Asset Relief Program, or TARP, have on average earned taxpayers 10.3% in annualized returns for their investments, according to Keefe Bruyette & Woods. and Morgan Stanley
, which each repaid their $10 billion in government investments last summer, generated returns of nearly 20% and 16%.
